</section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><h4 class="mbr-section-subtitle mbr-fonts-style mb-4 display-7">Why cannot we use pandas for large datasets?</h4></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
    <div class="container">
        <div class="row justify-content-center">
            <div class="col-md-12 col-lg-9"><p class="ff3" style="font-size:22px;">We do know that Pandas use computer memory (RAM) to load your datasets. But if your computer has a memory (RAM) of up to 8 GB, then why pandas is still unable or take time to load a 2 GB dataset? The reason is that loading a 2 GB file using Pandas does not only require 2 GB RAM but much more than that, because a total memory requirement is based on the size of the dataset along with the operations you are going to perform on that dataset, and even small projects contain plenty of pandas operations to accomplish the task.</p></div></div></div></section><section data-bs-version="5.1" class="content5 cid-tt5UseJ9wk" id="content5-4" style="padding-top:0px; padding-bottom:0px;background-color: rgb(255, 255, 255);">
